                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What number bases does this converter support?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>The converter supports binary (base 2), octal (base 8), decimal (base 10), and hexadecimal (base 16) — the four most commonly used number systems in computing. Enter a number in any base and instantly see it in all others.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why do programmers use hexadecimal?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Hexadecimal (hex) is compact and maps cleanly to binary — each hex digit represents exactly 4 bits. This makes it easy to read memory addresses, color codes, and binary data. For example, the byte 11111111 in binary is FF in hex, which is much easier to read and write.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between binary and hexadecimal?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Binary uses only 0 and 1 (base 2). Hexadecimal uses 0-9 and A-F (base 16). Both are used in computing, but hex is more compact — a byte (8 bits) takes 8 binary digits but only 2 hex digits. Programmers often use hex as a shorthand for binary.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I convert a hex color code to RGB?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Split the 6-digit hex code into three pairs: #RRGGBB. Convert each pair from hex to decimal. For example, #FF8000: FF = 255, 80 = 128, 00 = 0, so RGB(255, 128, 0). Use the Color Converter tool for a more convenient color-specific conversion.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is two's complement?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Two's complement is the standard way computers represent negative integers in binary. To negate a number: flip all bits (one's complement) then add 1. This system allows addition and subtraction to use the same hardware circuit, which is why it is universally used in CPUs.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>
